06708nam a22009495i 9781442670259DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172003onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426702597 a10.3138/97814426702592doi  a(DE-B1597)479191  a(OCoLC)987921841  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aSOC0260302bisacsh04a305.9069109704aThe World in a City /ced. by Paul Anisef, Michael Lanphier. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (528 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Immigration and the Accommodation of Diversity -- t1. Becoming an Immigrant City: A History of Immigration into Toronto since the Second World War -- t2. Immigrants in the Greater Toronto Area: A Sociodemographic Overview -- t3. Towards a Comfortable Neighbourhood and Appropriate Housing: Immigrant Experiences in Toronto -- t4. Immigrants’ Economic Status in Toronto: Stories of Triumph and Disappointment -- t5. Immigrant Students and Schooling in Toronto, 1960s to 1990s -- t6. Diversity and Immigrant Health -- t7. Images of Integrating Diversity: A Photographic Essay -- t8. Integrating Community Diversity in Toronto: On Whose Terms? -- t9. World in a City: A View from Policy -- tEpilogue: Blockages to Opportunity? -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToronto is perhaps the most multicultural city in the world. The process of settlement and integration in modern-day Toronto is, however, more difficult for recent immigrants than it was for those newcomers arriving in previous decades. Many challenges face newly settled immigrants, top among them access to healthcare, education, employment, housing, and other economic and community services. The concept of social exclusion opens up promising ways to analyze the various challenges facing newcomers and The World in a City explores Toronto's ability to sustain a civic society.This collection of essays highlights why the need to pay more attention to certain at-risk groups, and the importance of adapting policy to fit the changing settlement and clustering patterns of newcomers is of crucial importance. The authors' findings demonstrate that there are many obstacles to providing opportunity for immigrants, low resource bases in particular. Toronto, they suggest, does not provide a level 'playing field' for its newly arrived inhabitants, and, in failing to recognize the particular needs of new communities, fails to ensure a growth that would be of immense benefit to the city as a whole.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh1 aAnise, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnisef, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnisef, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurnaby, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurstein, Meyer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Carl E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJansen, Clifford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaspar, Violet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLam, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanphier, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanphier, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLo, Lucia, econt